                   "points": 20,
                   "difficulty": "hard",
                   "correctAnswer": "The set of all rational numbers is dense in the set of all real numbers because for any real number x and any positive real number epsilon, there exists a rational number r such that |x - r| < epsilon. To see this, let x be a real number and let epsilon be a positive real number. By the Archimedean property of the real numbers, there exists a positive integer n such that n > 1/epsilon. Let m be the largest integer such that m <= nx. Then m/n is a rational number and |x - m/n| = |(nx - m)/n| < 1/n < epsilon. Therefore, the set of all rational numbers is dense in the set of all real numbers.",
